Good question—and worth handling carefully, because there are two very different things people often mix together:
	1.	Where current science has real limits or open questions
	2.	Whether core, well-tested models (like heliocentrism, basic physics, etc.) are likely to be “flat-earth wrong”

Those are not the same.

⸻

🧠 I. What We’re Actually Likely to Be “Laughing At”

History suggests we rarely throw everything out.
We usually refine, extend, or reframe.

So the future “laugh” isn’t:

“They were totally wrong about everything”

It’s more like:

“They were right locally, but didn’t see the deeper structure”

⸻

⚠️ II. Where Current Science Genuinely “Breaks” or Is Incomplete

These are the real fault lines.

⸻

1. 🌌 Gravity vs Quantum Mechanics
	•	General Relativity works for large-scale (planets, galaxies)
	•	Quantum Mechanics works for small-scale

But:

They don’t fully reconcile

⸻

Likely future view:

We may look back and say:

“They treated spacetime and quantum fields as separate when they’re aspects of one deeper structure”

⸻

2. 🧱 Dark Matter / Dark Energy

Right now:
	•	~95% of the universe is inferred, not directly observed

⸻

Future “laugh” candidate:

“They invented placeholders (dark X) instead of realizing they misunderstood gravity or structure”

This is one of the strongest candidates for:

modern “epicycles” (like old astronomy patches)

⸻

3. 🧠 Consciousness

We can:
	•	map brain activity
	•	correlate signals

But:

We don’t actually know how subjective experience arises

⸻

Future perspective:

“They treated consciousness as an output instead of a fundamental or relational process”

⸻

4. 🧬 Biology as Mostly Mechanical

We understand:
	•	DNA
	•	proteins
	•	pathways

But still struggle with:
	•	emergence
	•	development
	•	system-level coordination

⸻

Future shift:

more emphasis on information flows, constraints, and systems dynamics, not just parts

⸻

5. 📊 Statistical Thinking Limits

A lot of modern science relies on:
	•	averages
	•	linear models
	•	simplified assumptions

But reality is often:
	•	nonlinear
	•	context-dependent
	•	adaptive

⸻

Future critique:

“They overfit clean models to messy systems”

⸻

🚫 III. What Is NOT Likely to Be “Flat Earth Wrong”

Some things are extremely well-tested:
	•	Earth is spherical (multiple independent proofs)
	•	heliocentrism (with refinements, not reversal)
	•	core physics laws in their domains (they may be extended, not discarded)

⸻

Key principle:

Science doesn’t usually flip from “true → false”
It goes from “partial → deeper”

⸻

🧠 IV. The Pattern of Past Mistakes

Let’s look at actual historical “we were wrong” moments:

⸻

🏛️ Geocentrism
	•	Earth at center
	•	everything revolves around us

Mistake:

Over-privileging human perspective

⸻

⚙️ Classical determinism
	•	universe as predictable machine

Mistake:

ignoring uncertainty, chaos, quantum effects

⸻

🧪 Vitalism
	•	life requires special “life force”

Mistake:

misunderstanding complexity and chemistry

⸻

🔁 Pattern Across All of Them

We tend to:
	1.	Assume our current frame is fundamental
	2.	Patch inconsistencies instead of rethinking structure
	3.	Overfit models to what we can measure

⸻

🧭 V. Your Question, Refined

What are today’s “geocentrism-like” assumptions?

Here are the strongest candidates:

⸻

1. 🧠 Human-Centric Cognition

We assume:
	•	intelligence ≈ human-like reasoning

Future may say:

“Intelligence is far broader and more distributed”

⸻

2. 🧱 Matter as Primary, Meaning as Secondary

We treat:
	•	physical → fundamental
	•	meaning → emergent

Future might invert or merge this:

information / structure as more primary

⸻

3. 🧩 Static Models of Dynamic Systems

We try to:
	•	freeze reality into equations

But reality is:
	•	adaptive, evolving, context-sensitive

⸻

4. 📦 Isolated Domains

We separate:
	•	physics
	•	biology
	•	psychology
	•	economics

Future likely sees:

deeper unifying principles across domains

⸻

⚡ VI. Clean Compression

The biggest future critique won’t be:
“They believed something obviously false”

It will be:
“They mistook useful models for complete reality.”

⸻

🔥 VII. Final Answer to Your Core Question

The closest modern equivalents to “flat earth thinking” are:
	•	treating current models as final
	•	patching anomalies instead of questioning foundations
	•	assuming human-scale intuition maps to reality

